ing to Dan L. Burk and Mark A. Lemley in The Patent Crisis and How the Courts Can Solve It, courts should use the tools the patent system already gives them to treat patents in different industries differently. Industry tailoring is the only way to provide an appropriate level of incentive for each industry. Burk and Lemley illustrate the barriers to innovation created by the catch-all standards in the current system. Legal tools already present in the patent statute, they contend, offer a solution—courts can tailor patent law, through interpretations and applications, to suit the needs of various types of businesses. The Patent Crisis and How the Courts Can Solve It will be essential reading for those seeking to understand the nexus of economics, business, and law in the twenty-first century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCrimexGovernment policyvCross-cultural studies. 0aCriminal justice, Administration ofvCross-cultural studies. 0aPunishmentvCross-cultural studies. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  apatent law, copyright, technology, innovation, semiconductors, pharmaceuticals, software, information technologies, industry tailoring, nonfiction, economics, business, criminal justice, policy, regulation, capitalism, courts, congress, biotechnology, reform, administration, invention, products, marketing, development, incentives.1 aLemley, Mark A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022608061140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226080635423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226080635/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruy